---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { withBase } from '../lib/basePath';
---

<Layout
  path="/theory"
  title="Theory"
  description="Light theory notes for Linear Algebra Lab — four subspaces architecture."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <span class="badge">Guide · light prose</span>
    <h1>How the pieces hang together</h1>
    <p>
      This is not a textbook. It is a map of what the desks already show.
    </p>

    <h2>One matrix, four subspaces</h2>
    <p>
      An m×n matrix A is a linear map ℚⁿ → ℚᵐ. It carves four subspaces:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>C(A)</strong> — column space in ℚᵐ (all outputs A x)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>N(A)</strong> — nullspace in ℚⁿ (inputs sent to 0)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>C(Aᵀ)</strong> — row space in ℚⁿ
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>N(Aᵀ)</strong> — left nullspace in ℚᵐ
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If rank(A) = r, the dimensions are r, n−r, r, m−r. That packing is the{' '}
      <a href={withBase('/theorems#four-subspaces')}>four fundamental subspaces</a>{' '}
      story (Strang’s framing).
    </p>

    <h2>RREF is bookkeeping</h2>
    <p>
      Reduced row echelon form does not invent new geometry — it renames variables
      so pivots and free columns are obvious. Pivot columns of A form a basis for
      C(A). Free columns build a basis for N(A). See the{' '}
      <a href={withBase('/matrix')}>matrix desk</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Solvability is membership</h2>
    <p>
      Ax = b has a solution exactly when b lies in C(A). When it does, solutions
      form an affine translate of N(A). The{' '}
      <a href={withBase('/solve')}>solve desk</a> makes that binary choice visible.
    </p>

    <h2>Orthogonal pairs</h2>
    <p>
      Over ℚ with the ordinary dot product, C(A) is orthogonal to N(Aᵀ), and C(Aᵀ)
      is orthogonal to N(A). The spaces desk runs those checks as green badges —
      implementation certificates, not formal proofs.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope</h2>
    <p>
      Exact rationals only in v0.1. Small matrices (catalog presets). No floating
      eigenvalues yet, no infinite-dimensional spaces, no formal proof assistant.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href={withBase('/spaces')}>Open the four subspaces desk →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>
